The paper deals with problems related to information theory, specifically network coding and secret sharing, which are typically categorized under cs.IT. The use of group theoretic techniques for combinatorial generation suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also discusses algorithms for solving the constrained linear representability problem, which is a combinatorial optimization problem, indicating a possible connection to algorithms and complexity (cs.CC). The implementation of an information theoretic achievability prover suggests a connection to networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) and systems and control (cs.SY).
